VALUES
(19, 59, 5, 5, 'kjv', 'awake to visit all the heathen:', 56, 87, 'question', 'Understanding Divine Visitations', 'What does it mean for God to ''visit'' the nations? In biblical terms, divine visitations often indicate a moment of judgment or blessing. How does this understanding shape our view of God''s involvement in global affairs today?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 59, 6, 6, 'kjv', 'They return at evening: they make a noise like a dog, and go round about the city.', 0, 82, 'connection', 'Similar Imagery', 'The imagery of dogs making noise is echoed in Philippians 3:2, where Paul warns against ''dogs'' as a metaphor for false teachers. This connection highlights the danger posed by those who roam and threaten the faithful, much like the enemies described in Psalm 59. Both passages emphasize vigilance against spiritual threats.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Philippians 3:2", "description": "Paul uses ''dogs'' metaphorically for false teachers."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 59, 6, 6, 'kjv', 'They return at evening: they make a noise like a dog, and go round about the city.', 0, 82, 'theology', 'Nature of Evil', 'This verse reflects the persistent nature of evil and its relentless pursuit of the righteous. Many scholars believe that the depiction of enemies as dogs suggests their uncleanliness and lack of dignity, which aligns with biblical themes of purity and holiness. This illustrates the ongoing spiritual battle faced by believers.', 'figure.mind.and.body', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 59, 6, 6, 'kjv', 'They return at evening: they make a noise like a dog, and go round about the city.', 0, 82, 'question', 'Understanding Vigilance', 'What does the imagery of ''returning at evening'' suggest about the timing of danger in our lives? How can we stay vigilant against threats that appear when we least expect them, especially in our spiritual walk?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 59, 6, 6, 'kjv', 'They return at evening: they make a noise like a dog, and go round about the city.', 0, 82, 'greek', 'Key Term - Noise', 'φωνὴ (phōnē, G5456) - sound, voice, noise. This term emphasizes the disruptive nature of the enemies'' actions, likening them to an alarming sound that demands attention. It signifies not just physical noise but also the chaos they represent in the spiritual realm.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G5456", "description": "Phon\u0113 refers to sound or noise."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 59, 7, 7, 'kjv', 'they belch out with their mouth', 8, 39, 'connection', 'Speech as a Weapon', 'This phrase resonates with James 3:6, which states, ''And the tongue is a fire, a world of iniquity.'' Both passages highlight the destructive power of speech. In Psalm 59:7, the ''belching'' signifies not only a verbal assault but also an unrestrained expression of malice, illustrating how words can be weapons against others, echoing the warning in James about the potential of the tongue to cause great harm.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "James 3:6", "description": "This verse underscores the destructive potential of uncontrolled speech, akin to the imagery in Psalm 59."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 59, 7, 7, 'kjv', 'swords are in their lips', 41, 65, 'theology', 'Power of Words', 'Many scholars believe this imagery suggests that words can be as lethal as swords. The doctrine of the power of speech emphasizes that words can either build up or tear down. In the context of spiritual warfare, the psalmist conveys that the enemies'' falsehoods and threats can cause real harm, mirroring the teachings found in Proverbs 18:21, which states, ''Death and life are in the power of the tongue.''', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Proverbs 18:21", "description": "This verse highlights the significance of speech, paralleling the metaphor of swords in Psalm 59."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 59, 7, 7, 'kjv', 'for who, say they, doth hear?', 67, 96, 'question', 'Divine Awareness', 'What does this question reveal about the nature of accountability before God? The enemies believe their words are unobserved and without consequence. How does this perception of divine silence challenge your understanding of God''s omnipresence and justice? Reflecting on this can deepen your awareness of how God hears and sees all, even when it seems otherwise.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 59, 8, 8, 'kjv', 'thou, O Lord, shalt laugh at them;', 4, 38, 'connection', 'Divine Laughter', 'This phrase echoes Psalm 2:4, where God is depicted as laughing at the nations conspiring against Him. The connection underscores God''s sovereignty and the futility of opposing His will, reinforcing the assurance that He is in control despite worldly chaos.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 2:4", "description": "God''s laughter at earthly rebellion."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 59, 8, 8, 'kjv', 'thou shalt have all the heathen in derision.', 39, 83, 'theology', 'God''s Judgment on Nations', 'Many scholars believe this verse reflects the broader theological theme of God''s ultimate judgment on nations that reject Him. It highlights the contrast between divine justice and human folly, illustrating that God''s plans will prevail over human schemes.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 59, 8, 8, 'kjv', 'thou, O Lord, shalt laugh at them;', 4, 38, 'greek', 'Hebrew ''לָעַג'' (la''ag)', 'לָעַג (la''ag, H3932) - to mock, to deride. This term emphasizes not just laughter but a scornful derision, indicating God''s disdain for those who oppose His authority, affirming His role as the righteous judge.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H3932", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 59, 8, 8, 'kjv', 'thou shalt have all the heathen in derision.', 39, 83, 'question', 'Understanding Divine Mockery', 'What does it reveal about God''s character that He would mock those who oppose Him? How does this understanding influence your view of justice and righteousness in the world today?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 59, 9, 9, 'kjv', 'Because of his strength', 0, 23, 'connection', 'Strength of the Lord', 'This phrase connects with Psalms 28:7, which states, ''The Lord is my strength and my shield; my heart trusts in him, and he helps me.'' This emphasizes the theme of reliance on God''s power for protection and support, reinforcing the psalmist''s faith in divine strength amidst adversity.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalms 28:7", "description": "Highlights the Lord as a source of strength."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 59, 9, 9, 'kjv', 'will I wait upon thee', 24, 45, 'question', 'Waiting on God', 'What does it mean to truly ''wait upon'' God in the context of our daily struggles? This phrase invites us to consider how patience and trust in God''s timing can shape our responses to challenges, encouraging us to seek His guidance rather than relying solely on our own strength.', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 59, 9, 9, 'kjv', 'for God is my defence.', 47, 69, 'theology', 'God as Defense', 'This passage reflects the theological concept of God as a refuge and protector. Many scholars believe this aligns with the broader biblical narrative where God is consistently portrayed as a fortress for His people (see Psalms 91:2). It reassures believers of God’s active role in their defense against spiritual and physical threats.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalms 91:2", "description": "Describes God as a refuge."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 59, 9, 9, 'kjv', 'for God is my defence.', 47, 69, 'greek', 'Defence in Hebrew', 'מָגֵן (magen, H4043) - shield, defense. This Hebrew term indicates a protective barrier, emphasizing God''s role not only as a defender but as a personal protector in times of trouble, illustrating the intimate relationship between God and His followers.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H4043", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word for ''defence.''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 59, 10, 10, 'kjv', 'The God of my mercy shall prevent me', 0, 36, 'connection', 'Divine Mercy Connection', 'This phrase resonates with Psalm  mercy themes found in Psalm 86:5, which states, ''For you, Lord, are good, and ready to forgive, and abundant in mercy to all those who call upon You.'' Both passages highlight God''s character as merciful and ready to assist those in need, emphasizing the trust the psalmist places in God''s protective mercy.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 86:5", "description": "Highlights God''s readiness to forgive and show mercy."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 59, 10, 10, 'kjv', 'God shall let me see my desire upon mine enemies', 38, 86, 'theology', 'Desire for Justice', 'Many scholars believe this verse reflects a theological understanding of God''s justice and the hope for vindication against adversaries. The desire mentioned is not purely vengeful but aligns with God''s righteousness, suggesting that the psalmist seeks divine intervention to bring about a just outcome rather than personal revenge.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the themes of divine justice and vindication in the Psalms."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 59, 10, 10, 'kjv', 'The God of my mercy shall prevent me', 0, 36, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Mercy''', 'חֶסֶד (chesed, H2617) - lovingkindness, mercy. This Hebrew term encapsulates a deep, covenantal love and loyalty. It emphasizes not only God''s mercy but His commitment to His people, suggesting that the psalmist''s confidence is rooted in the relational fidelity of God.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H2617", "description": "Strong''s entry for the Hebrew word for mercy."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 59, 10, 10, 'kjv', 'God shall let me see my desire upon mine enemies', 38, 86, 'question', 'Reflection on Desire', 'What does it mean to desire justice against our enemies in light of God''s mercy? How can we balance our longing for vindication with the call to love and forgive those who oppose us?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 59, 11, 11, 'kjv', 'Slay them not, lest my people forget:', 0, 37, 'connection', 'Remembering God''s Deliverance', 'This phrase echoes Deuteronomy 8:2, where Israel is reminded to remember the Lord''s guidance and provision during their wilderness journey. The concern expressed here is that if enemies are swiftly dealt with, the people might forget the lessons learned from God''s deliverance. Remembering God''s past actions is crucial for sustaining faith and reliance on Him.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Deuteronomy 8:2", "description": "A reminder to remember God''s faithfulness."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 59, 11, 11, 'kjv', 'scatter them by thy power;', 38, 64, 'theology', 'God''s Sovereign Power', 'This plea reflects the belief in God''s sovereignty over nations and circumstances. Many scholars believe this demonstrates a reliance on God''s might rather than human strength. The request to scatter enemies rather than destroy them suggests a desire for God''s power to be evident, reinforcing the idea that God''s authority is paramount in both judgment and mercy.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 59, 11, 11, 'kjv', 'O Lord our shield.', 86, 104, 'greek', 'Divine Protection', 'שִׁילְד (magen, H4043) - shield, defense. The Hebrew term emphasizes God''s role as protector in times of distress. By invoking God as ''our shield,'' the psalmist acknowledges reliance on divine strength against adversaries, highlighting the protective nature of faith in God.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H4043", "description": "Strong''s number for ''shield'' in Hebrew."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 59, 11, 11, 'kjv', 'Slay them not, lest my people forget:', 0, 37, 'question', 'Importance of Memory', 'What does it mean for our faith if we forget the struggles and victories God has led us through? How can remembering past deliverances shape our responses to current challenges?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 59, 12, 12, 'kjv', 'the sin of their mouth', 4, 26, 'connection', 'Connection to Proverbs', 'This phrase resonates with Proverbs 18:21, which states, ''Death and life are in the power of the tongue.'' Both passages highlight the significant impact of speech and the moral responsibility that comes with it. In Psalm 59, the sin of the mouth is directly linked to pride and deceit, emphasizing that words can lead to severe consequences, both for the speaker and others.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Proverbs 18:21", "description": "Highlights the power of words in determining outcomes."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 59, 12, 12, 'kjv', 'cursing and lying', 102, 119, 'theology', 'Nature of Sinful Speech', 'This passage underscores the serious nature of sinful speech, specifically cursing and lying. Many scholars believe that these actions represent a violation of the commandment to love one''s neighbor, as articulated in James 3:9-10, where it discusses the inconsistency of blessing God while cursing others. Theological implications suggest that such speech reflects a deeper moral and spiritual corruption.', 'person.2.fill', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 59, 12, 12, 'kjv', 'let them even be taken in their pride', 55, 92, 'question', 'Pride''s Consequences', 'What does it reveal about human nature that pride often precedes downfall, as suggested in this verse? How can recognizing the dangers of pride shape our interactions with others and our relationship with God?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 59, 12, 12, 'kjv', 'words of their lips', 35, 54, 'greek', 'Significance of ''Lips''', 'שפתים (s''phatim, H8193) - lips, speech. This Hebrew term emphasizes the physical manifestation of speech and its importance in communication. It indicates that the words spoken have a tangible effect on relationships and community dynamics, highlighting the weight of one''s spoken words.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H8193", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term related to speech."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 59, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'Consume them in wrath, consume them, that they may not be:', 0, 58, 'connection', 'Divine Judgment Theme', 'This phrase resonates with Psalms 2:5, where God speaks to the nations in His wrath. Both passages highlight God''s authority and the seriousness of divine judgment against those who oppose Him. Understanding this context deepens the reader''s appreciation of God''s sovereignty and the urgency of repentance.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalms 2:5", "description": "God''s wrath against nations"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 59, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'let them know that God ruleth in Jacob unto the ends of the earth.', 63, 129, 'theology', 'God''s Sovereignty', 'This passage suggests a fundamental Christian belief in God''s sovereignty over all creation. The reference to Jacob signifies God''s covenantal relationship with His people, emphasizing that His reign extends beyond Israel to the entire earth, affirming His ultimate authority and plan for redemption.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 59, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'that they may not be:', 37, 58, 'question', 'Existential Reflection', 'What does it mean for those who oppose God to ''not be''? How does this understanding of judgment influence our view of justice and mercy within our own lives and communities?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 59, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'Consume them in wrath, consume them,', 0, 36, 'greek', 'Hebrew Emotion', 'אָכַל (akal, H398) - consume, eat. This term conveys a strong sense of total destruction, often used in contexts of divine judgment. The repetition emphasizes the intensity of God''s wrath, reflecting the seriousness with which God addresses sin and rebellion.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H398", "description": "Strong''s Hebrew number for ''consume''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 59, 14, 14, 'kjv', 'And at evening let them return;', 0, 31, 'connection', 'Evening Returns in Scripture', 'The phrase ''at evening let them return'' echoes the sentiment found in Lamentations 3:22-23, where God’s mercies are said to be new every morning. This juxtaposition of evening and morning highlights the cyclical nature of despair and hope in the believer''s life. The evening represents the struggles and trials, while the return signifies the hope of redemption and restoration.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Lamentations 3:22-23", "description": "Highlights the contrast between evening trials and morning mercies."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 59, 14, 14, 'kjv', 'make a noise like a dog,', 45, 69, 'theology', 'Symbolism of Dogs', 'The imagery of dogs making noise presents a picture of desperation and base instincts. In biblical times, dogs were often viewed as unclean animals, symbolizing those who are outside of God''s covenant. This suggests that the enemies of the psalmist are in a state of spiritual depravity, acting out of primal hunger and need, reminding readers of the spiritual warfare against those who oppose God''s ways.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 59, 14, 14, 'kjv', 'and go round about the city.', 70, 98, 'question', 'Meaning of Circling', 'What does it signify for the enemies to ''go round about the city''? Could this reflect the idea of persistent threats that surround the faithful? In what ways do we recognize the spiritual battles that encircle our lives, and how might we respond in faith rather than fear?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 59, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'Let them wander up and down for meat, and grudge if they be not satisfied.', 0, 74, 'connection', 'Wandering for Provision', 'This verse parallels Psalm 37:25, where David states, ''I have been young, and now am old; yet have I not seen the righteous forsaken, nor his seed begging bread.'' Both passages reflect on the theme of divine provision and the struggles faced by the wicked. The connection highlights the contrast between the fate of the unrighteous, who are depicted as wandering and unsatisfied, and the assurance of God''s provision for the faithful.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 37:25", "description": "Highlights God''s provision for the righteous."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 59, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'Let them wander up and down for meat, and grudge if they be not satisfied.', 0, 74, 'theology', 'The Nature of Discontent', 'This passage suggests a theological reflection on human discontent and the consequences of sin. Many scholars believe that the imagery of wandering and grumbling illustrates the spiritual emptiness that accompanies a life apart from God. The longing for sustenance can be seen as a metaphor for the deeper spiritual hunger that only God can fulfill, underscoring the importance of reliance on divine provision for true satisfaction.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 59, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'Let them wander up and down for meat, and grudge if they be not satisfied.', 0, 74, 'question', 'Wandering and Satisfaction', 'What does this verse reveal about the nature of true satisfaction in our lives? As the wicked wander in search of meat and grumble when they do not find it, how can we ensure that our needs are met in a way that aligns with God''s will? Reflecting on this may lead us to consider what it means to seek fulfillment in our spiritual journey.', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 59, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'sing of thy power', 11, 28, 'connection', 'God''s Power in Psalms', 'This phrase invites a comparison with Psalm 66:1-3, where the psalmist calls upon all the earth to sing of God''s glory and power. This connection highlights the communal aspect of worship and the recognition of God''s might as central to the faith experience, reinforcing the theme of praising God for His omnipotence.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 66:1-3", "description": "Another psalm emphasizing the call to praise God''s power."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 59, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'thy mercy in the morning', 56, 80, 'theology', 'The Nature of God''s Mercy', 'This line reflects the theological concept of God''s steadfast love and mercy, which is renewed each day. Many scholars believe that this daily renewal of mercy, akin to Lamentations 3:22-23, underscores the hope and assurance believers find in God, suggesting that each morning is an opportunity for fresh grace.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Lamentations 3:22-23", "description": "Verses that speak to God''s mercies being new every morning."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 59, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'defence and refuge', 104, 122, 'greek', 'Meaning of ''Defence''', 'מָגֵן (magen, H4043) - shield, protector. This term emphasizes God’s role as a protector and source of strength in times of trouble, illustrating His active involvement in providing safety and support to believers.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H4043", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term meaning ''shield'' or ''defense.''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 59, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'in the day of my trouble', 123, 147, 'question', 'Experiencing God''s Refuge', 'What does it mean for you to find refuge in God during your own troubles? How can recalling His past deliverance strengthen your faith in current challenges, as indicated in this verse?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 59, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'Unto thee, O my strength', 0, 24, 'connection', 'Divine Strength Across Scripture', 'The phrase ''O my strength'' echoes Psalm 18:1, where David declares, ''I will love thee, O LORD, my strength.'' Both verses highlight God as the ultimate source of strength in times of distress. This connection emphasizes the intimate relationship between the believer and God, reinforcing the notion that reliance on divine strength is foundational in the believer''s life.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 18:1", "description": "David acknowledges God as his strength."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 59, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'for God is my defence', 39, 60, 'theology', 'God as Defender', 'This passage reveals a central tenet of Christian theology: God as our defender and protector. Many scholars believe that this reflects the broader biblical narrative of God safeguarding His people, as seen in Isaiah 54:17, which states that ''no weapon formed against you shall prosper.'' This assurance of divine protection is integral to understanding God''s covenant relationship with humanity.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Isaiah 54:17", "description": "God''s promise of protection against adversaries."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 59, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'the God of my mercy', 66, 85, 'greek', 'Understanding Mercy', 'רָחָם (racham, H7355) - mercy, compassion. This Hebrew term emphasizes the deep, familial compassion God has for His people, akin to a mother''s love. When David refers to God as ''the God of my mercy,'' he underscores the personal and relational aspect of God''s character, which is crucial in understanding the nature of divine mercy within the context of human need.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H7355", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word for mercy."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 59, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'for God is my defence', 39, 60, 'question', 'Reflection on God''s Protection', 'How does understanding God as ''my defence'' influence your trust in Him during times of trouble? Reflecting on this phrase invites deeper contemplation about the nature of divine safeguarding and the assurance it provides amidst life''s challenges.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 60, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'O God, thou hast cast us off, thou hast scattered us, thou hast been displeased; O turn thyself to us again.', 0, 108, 'connection', 'Divine Displeasure', 'This verse resonates with Lamentations 5:20, where the plea for God''s attention follows a period of suffering and abandonment. Both passages highlight the deep yearning for divine restoration after experiencing God''s displeasure. Understanding this connection emphasizes the communal aspect of lamentation in Scripture, showcasing that the people often express their distress collectively, seeking God''s mercy.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Lamentations 5:20", "description": "Another cry for God''s attention after suffering."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 60, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'thou hast cast us off', 7, 28, 'theology', 'God''s Discipline', 'Many scholars believe this phrase reflects God''s use of discipline as a means of correction for His people. The act of being cast off can be seen as a necessary response to sin, allowing for the possibility of repentance and restoration. This understanding aligns with Hebrews 12:6, which states that the Lord disciplines those He loves, emphasizing the redemptive nature of God''s displeasure.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Hebrews 12:6", "description": "Discusses God''s discipline as an act of love."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 60, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'O turn thyself to us again.', 81, 108, 'question', 'Seeking God''s Presence', 'What does it mean for you personally when you ask God to ''turn thyself to us again''? Consider the implications of seeking divine presence and how it shapes your relationship with God. How might this prayer reflect your own experiences of feeling distant from God and longing for restoration?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 60, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'Thou hast made the earth to tremble;', 0, 36, 'connection', 'Cosmic Disturbance', 'This phrase resonates with Isaiah 24:19-20, which describes the earth as breaking and shaking under divine judgment. The connection highlights God''s sovereignty over creation and serves as a reminder of the consequences of human sin, echoing the call for repentance and restoration. Understanding this cosmic disturbance deepens our awareness of God''s power and His role in the created order.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Isaiah 24:19-20", "description": "Illustrates the earth trembling as a result of God''s judgment."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini');